{"Body": "<h3><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">The Sunday Business Post will tomorrow carry details of the government's four-year budgetary plan, which will subject to a \"thorough examination\" by the European Commission/IMF. According to Irish Examiner journalist Tom Hickey, the plan includes a registration fee increase of &euro;700, a 47% increase. He posted a series of figures <a href=\"http://twitter.com/1TomHickey\">to his Twitter account</a>&nbsp;this evening. No specific figures were released relating to the student grant.</span></span></span></h3>\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Additional measures he has claimed to be in the plan include a cut to the minimum wage, and an average of 11% cut to social welfare payments by 2014. A levy on public-sector pensions is liable to cause unrest, as one of the country's largest Trades Unions, the Technical Engineering and Electrical Union (TEEU), voting overwhelmingly in favour of a campaign of civil disobedience if the Government does not call a General Election.</span></span></h3>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: small;\">The four-year plan underlines the Government's opposition to any increases to the 12.5% corporation tax rate. French President Nicolas Sarkozy said today that he expects that Ireland will raise its tax rate, but also noted that the bailout is not subject to any \"fiscal demands\". Minister for Finance Brian Lenihan said that the tax rate was an \"absolute red-line issue\" for the Government. Many European countries feel that Ireland's low business tax rate amounts to unfair tax competition for foreign investment, but it has made Ireland a very attractive location for inward investment, with foreign companies accounting for 150,000 jobs here.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: small;\">The figure of &euro;2,200 for the Registration Fee will be met with a mixture of joy and disappointment by USI - although a smaller increase than was anticipated in advance of the November 3rd protest, the level of the fee is now unlikely to decrease from this point and may still increase depending on the opinions of the European Commission and IMF - who are basically immune to any pressure that Students' Unions can exert.</span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>", "Imageurl": "<h3><span style=\"font-size: small;\"><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">The Sunday Business Post will tomorrow carry details of the government's four-year budgetary plan, which will subject to a \"thorough examination\" by the European Commission/IMF. According to Irish Examiner journalist Tom Hickey, the plan includes a registration fee increase of &euro;700, a 47% increase. He posted a series of figures <a href=\"http://twitter.com/1TomHickey\">to his Twitter account</a>&nbsp;this evening. No specific figures were released relating to the student grant.</span></span></span></h3>\n<h3><span style=\"font-weight: normal;\"><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Additional measures he has claimed to be in the plan include a cut to the minimum wage, and an average of 11% cut to social welfare payments by 2014. A levy on public-sector pensions is liable to cause unrest, as one of the country's largest Trades Unions, the Technical Engineering and Electrical Union (TEEU), voting overwhelmingly in favour of a campaign of civil disobedience if the Government does not call a General Election.</span></span></h3>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: small;\">The four-year plan underlines the Government's opposition to any increases to the 12.5% corporation tax rate. French President Nicolas Sarkozy said today that he expects that Ireland will raise its tax rate, but also noted that the bailout is not subject to any \"fiscal demands\". Minister for Finance Brian Lenihan said that the tax rate was an \"absolute red-line issue\" for the Government. Many European countries feel that Ireland's low business tax rate amounts to unfair tax competition for foreign investment, but it has made Ireland a very attractive location for inward investment, with foreign companies accounting for 150,000 jobs here.</span></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-size: small;\">The figure of &euro;2,200 for the Registration Fee will be met with a mixture of joy and disappointment by USI - although a smaller increase than was anticipated in advance of the November 3rd protest, the level of the fee is now unlikely to decrease from this point and may still increase depending on the opinions of the European Commission and IMF - who are basically immune to any pressure that Students' Unions can exert.</span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "794", "Heading": "Government's four-year plan to include &euro;700 Registration Fee hike"}